<tr><td>Fri 1/24 - Sun 1/26</td>
<td><b>The Great Gulf War</b><br>Robert Zeithammer (rzeitham@mit.edu) will be leading a trip to go untrodden places in the Great Gulf with lots of snow and ascend big mountains without hte aid of trails. Fri snowshoe into the Great Gulf, build snowshelters to stay in, ascend Mt. Jefferson via the Six Husbands Ridge. Maybe Washington. Next day another shot at Washington or Adams. Walk out on Sun PM, crash at Intervale and get back to Boston on Monday before noon. Or maybe only walk out Mon AM. <br>
Equipment: sleeping bags, pads, shovels, big snowshoes, ice-axes, crampons.<br>
Pre-reqs: a positive reference from a trusted MITOC winter school leader, ability to potentially complete in a single push (13 miles, 7000 ft. up, some deep snow)
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>Sat 1/25</td><td><b>Franconia Ridge - Above Treeline</b><br>
Rob Jagnow (rjagnow@mit.edu) and Stan Jurga (jurga@mit.edu) will lead a day trip to Franconia Ridge on Saturday. Leaving Fri night, staying at Camelot, up early. Up by Falling Waters Trail, down by Green Leaf and Old Bridal Path.<br>
Equipment: snowshoes, crampons, trekking poles, ice axe?<br>
Other requirements: full above treeline clothing</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Fri 1/24 - Sat 1/25</td><td><b>Extreme Sledding</b><br>
Led by Jason Lapenta (lapenta_jm@yahoo.com), David Comi and Yoko Miyata. <br>
This trip is in no way considered safe. Like
rock-climbing and ice-climbing it carries serious 
risks, like running into trees, being buried by 
avalanches, dying of exhaustion, sliding off 
mountains and freezing to death. This trip is for 
people experienced with dealing with long hikes, 
extreme cold, have the proper gear and are familiar 
with it's limits, can go zero exposure (mask
goggles, etc), are not afraid or heights or going 
fast down steep slopes or weaving between trees 
on a single track trails. Must be prepared for 
hiking all day and all night to go sledding.
<br>
Drive up Friday Night, buy sled. Make a base camp at
Intervale. Depending on weather and conditions we 
will sled near Mt. Washington and possible Wildcat Mtn. 
There is no way to set a location because it is 
highly weather dependent.
<br>
Saturday we will sled all day and into the night. 
Coming back late. Sunday will depend on how whooped 
we are on what we do but probably more sledding. 
<br>
I don't think mouse boots are going to cut it
for this trip, but I've never hiked in mouse 
boot. What do you more experienced leaders think?
<br>
Gear:

Keep packs light for fun sledding.

Luge sled,
Full winter gear,
headlamp,
Two insulated nalgenes,
Gorp,
Insulated winter boots sorrels or equivalent,
* Crampons w/prior experience,
Gaiters,
* ice axe, 
* pack with ax loops.<br>

Endurance to keep moving in the cold all day.
Above treeline experience.
Self arrest experience.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
